ndency already exists. I’m wondering if the existing tests are sufficient or if additional properties are needed for JDK9+ access. I need to finalize a strategy for meaningful coverage that includes possible system property instructions as well.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating advisory preparations**\\n\\nI’m considering whether we should recommend advisory preparation using `agent_guidance` for tests involving non-public `java.lang` reflection or the `AccessibleObjectHandlerJDK9Plus`. It requires a JVM argument `--add-opens`, but I’m questioning if it’s really necessary for meaningful coverage. OGNL can be effectively covered without it, so it seems like no action might be needed unless there's evidence suggesting extra setup is required. I also want to check if existing setups cover everything without needing additional configurations.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering security manager settings**\\n\\nI’m looking at changes in Java 18+, which now defaults to disallowing `System.setSecurityManager` unless the property `java.security.manager=allow` is set. Existing tests are designed to skip this step if it's not allowed. To achieve meaningful coverage for `OgnlSecurityManager`, I’d need to include `-Djava.security.manager=allow`, but I’m wondering if this setting might be impossible to implement in JDK 25. It feels like navigating these restrictions could be tricky!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_iMPsN5CyuPh5Ffdod11qQRQJ|fc_08bc78dab4c702e1016a4204d45c10819793a8e0652d32a946", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "cd tests/src/ognl/ognl/3.2.21 && env GVM_TCK_LV=3.3.5 ../../../../../gradlew test --tests ognl.ognl.ObjectPropertyAccessorTest.invokesWriteMethodFallbackWhenAccessCheckRejectsRegularSetterPath -Dognl.UseStricterInvocation=false -Dognl.UseFirstMatchGetSetLookup=true --stacktrace", "timeout": 120}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1075, "output"